	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="1641176949" id="dsq-comment-1641176949">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="https://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-1641176949">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2014-10-17</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-1641176949" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-1641176949" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hey Nick!</p><p>Great question! And this is tricky. The short answer is that you can't (and should not) get the container in an entity. Instead, create a separate service (e.g. PathManager) that is able to give you what you want. So:</p><p></p><pre><code><br>$image = // ... query for some Image entity object<br><br><br>// don't try to do this, because that function would need the container<br>$path = $image-&gt;getFilenameWithPrefix()<br><br><br>// instead, grab a service that has your parameter injected into it<br>$path = $this-&gt;container-&gt;get('my_path_manager_service')-&gt;getImagePath($image);<br></code></pre><p></p><p>This is lacking some details, but there's a big philosophical difference that I hope you see! If not, let me know!</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
